1 La estructura de los datos

DespuÃ©s de instalar hay que cargar las librerÃ­as para esta sesiÃ³n

library(SingleCellExperiment)

1.1 Cargar los datos experimentales

En esta parte simularemos tablas de cuentas de genes por cÃ©lula

counts_matrix <- data.frame(cell_1 = rpois(10, 10), 
                    cell_2 = rpois(10, 10), 
                    cell_3 = rpois(10, 30))
rownames(counts_matrix) <- paste0("gene_", 1:10)
counts_matrix <- as.matrix(counts_matrix) # must be a matrix object!
  1. Checar que se trate de un objeto tipo matriz
  2. Â¿De quÃ© dimesniÃ³n es?
  3. Â¿QuÃ© significan los renglones y que las columnas?
  4. Â¿QuÃ© hace la funciÃ³n rpois()?

Para convertir esta matriz en un objeto de tipo single cell experiment usamos la funciÃ³n del paquete que acabamos de cargar SingleCellExperiment()

sce <- SingleCellExperiment(assays = list(counts = counts_matrix))

Para visualizar la estructura de ese objeto podemos teclear el nombre que le asignamos o utilizar la funciÃ³n str(). Esta Ãºltima funciÃ³n es mÃ¡s poderosa porque arroja mÃ¡s informaciÃ³n pero , a menudo, es demasiada informaciÃ³n para que uno pueda procesarla.

1.2 Agregar mÃ¡s assays

Esto puede ser Ãºtil, por ejemplo en una situaciÃ³n en donde podemos tener en un sÃ³lo objeto la versiÃ³n cruda de los datos y la versiÃ³n normalizada en el mismo, de tal forma que asÃ­ no perdemos informaciÃ³n.

sce <- scater::logNormCounts(sce)

Ahora vemos lo que sucede con el objeto

sce 
## class: SingleCellExperiment 
## dim: 10 3 
## metadata(0):
## assays(2): counts logcounts
## rownames(10): gene_1 gene_2 ... gene_9 gene_10
## rowData names(0):
## colnames(3): cell_1 cell_2 cell_3
## colData names(1): sizeFactor
## reducedDimNames(0):
## altExpNames(0):
  1. Compara quÃ© sale en la parte de assays con respecto al objeto original

Si quisieramos acceder a estas Ãºltimas cuentas podemos usar la funciÃ³n logcounts()

Podemos ver especÃ­ficamente cuÃ¡ntos assays tiene el objeto sce

assays(sce)
## List of length 2
## names(2): counts logcounts

Podemos hacer esta operaciÃ³n manual, es decir que no lo ha automÃ¡tico

counts_100 <- counts(sce) + 100
assay(sce, "counts_100") <- counts_100 # assign a new entry to assays slot
assays(sce) # new assay has now been added.
## List of length 3
## names(3): counts logcounts counts_100

1.3 Metadatos

Todas las bases tienen metadatos. Los metadatos son toda aquella informaciÃ³n adicional que nos permite interpretar los datos, por ejmplo, si la muestra viene de cierto tipo de pacientes: edad, gÃ©nero, condicÃ³n fÃ­sica, etc.

1.3.1 Pro columnas

cell_metadata <- data.frame(batch = c(1, 1, 2))
rownames(cell_metadata) <- paste0("cell_", 1:3)
sce <- SingleCellExperiment(assays = list(counts = counts_matrix),
    colData = cell_metadata)

2 Para lxs impacientes: scRNAseq en un sÃ³lo paso

library(scRNAseq)
sce <- MacoskoRetinaData()
## snapshotDate(): 2020-04-27
## see ?scRNAseq and browseVignettes('scRNAseq') for documentation
## loading from cache
## see ?scRNAseq and browseVignettes('scRNAseq') for documentation
## loading from cache
# Objeto pesado 

# Quality control.
library(scater)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
is.mito <- grepl("^MT-", rownames(sce))
qcstats <- perCellQCMetrics(sce, subsets=list(Mito=is.mito))
filtered <- quickPerCellQC(qcstats, percent_subsets="subsets_Mito_percent")
sce <- sce[, !filtered$discard]

# Normalization.
sce <- logNormCounts(sce)

# Feature selection.
library(scran)
dec <- modelGeneVar(sce)
hvg <- getTopHVGs(dec, prop=0.1)

# Dimensionality reduction.
set.seed(1234)
sce <- runPCA(sce, ncomponents=25, subset_row=hvg)
sce <- runUMAP(sce, dimred = 'PCA', external_neighbors=TRUE)

# Clustering.
g <- buildSNNGraph(sce, use.dimred = 'PCA')
colLabels(sce) <- factor(igraph::cluster_louvain(g)$membership)

# Visualization.
plotUMAP(sce, colour_by="label")

3.1 PCA

library(scRNAseq)
sce.zeisel <- ZeiselBrainData()
## snapshotDate(): 2020-04-27
## see ?scRNAseq and browseVignettes('scRNAseq') for documentation
## loading from cache
## see ?scRNAseq and browseVignettes('scRNAseq') for documentation
## loading from cache
## see ?scRNAseq and browseVignettes('scRNAseq') for documentation
## loading from cache
## snapshotDate(): 2020-04-27
## see ?scRNAseq and browseVignettes('scRNAseq') for documentation
## loading from cache
library(scater)
sce.zeisel <- aggregateAcrossFeatures(sce.zeisel, 
    id=sub("_loc[0-9]+$", "", rownames(sce.zeisel)))

#--- gene-annotation ---#
library(org.Mm.eg.db)
## Loading required package: AnnotationDbi
## 
rowData(sce.zeisel)$Ensembl <- mapIds(org.Mm.eg.db, 
    keys=rownames(sce.zeisel), keytype="SYMBOL", column="ENSEMBL")
## 'select()' returned 1:many mapping between keys and columns
#--- quality-control ---#
stats <- perCellQCMetrics(sce.zeisel, subsets=list(
    Mt=rowData(sce.zeisel)$featureType=="mito"))
qc <- quickPerCellQC(stats, percent_subsets=c("altexps_ERCC_percent", 
    "subsets_Mt_percent"))
sce.zeisel <- sce.zeisel[,!qc$discard]

#--- normalization ---#
library(scran)
set.seed(1000)
clusters <- quickCluster(sce.zeisel)
sce.zeisel <- computeSumFactors(sce.zeisel, cluster=clusters) 
sce.zeisel <- logNormCounts(sce.zeisel)

#--- variance-modelling ---#
dec.zeisel <- modelGeneVarWithSpikes(sce.zeisel, "ERCC")
top.hvgs <- getTopHVGs(dec.zeisel, prop=0.1)
BiocManager::install("PCAtools")
## Bioconductor version 3.11 (BiocManager 1.30.12), R 4.0.3 (2020-10-10)
## Installing package(s) 'PCAtools'
## 
## The downloaded binary packages are in
##  /var/folders/sg/t89hzm1d20v0824kv94s7n380000gn/T//Rtmp5Tiz23/downloaded_packages
library(scran)
top.zeisel <- getTopHVGs(dec.zeisel, n=2000)

library(scater)
set.seed(100) # See below.
sce.zeisel <- runPCA(sce.zeisel, subset_row=top.zeisel) 
reducedDimNames(sce.zeisel)
## [1] "PCA"
library(BiocSingular)
set.seed(1000)
sce.zeisel <- runPCA(sce.zeisel, subset_row=top.zeisel, 
    BSPARAM=RandomParam(), name="IRLBA")
reducedDimNames(sce.zeisel)
## [1] "PCA"   "IRLBA"
percent.var <- attr(reducedDim(sce.zeisel), "percentVar")
plot(percent.var, log="y", xlab="PC", ylab="Variance explained (%)")

percent.var <- attr(reducedDim(sce.zeisel), "percentVar")
chosen.elbow <- PCAtools::findElbowPoint(percent.var)
chosen.elbow
## [1] 7
plot(percent.var, xlab="PC", ylab="Variance explained (%)")
abline(v=chosen.elbow, col="red")

# Creating a new entry with only the first 20 PCs, 
# useful if we still need the full set of PCs later. 
reducedDim(sce.zeisel, "PCA.elbow") <- reducedDim(sce.zeisel)[,1:chosen.elbow]
reducedDimNames(sce.zeisel)
## [1] "PCA"       "IRLBA"     "PCA.elbow"
# Alternatively, just overwriting the original PCA entry. For demonstration
# purposes, we'll do this to a copy so that we still have full PCs later on.
sce.zeisel.copy <- sce.zeisel 
reducedDim(sce.zeisel.copy) <- reducedDim(sce.zeisel.copy)[,1:chosen.elbow]
ncol(reducedDim(sce.zeisel.copy))
## [1] 7
plotReducedDim(sce.zeisel, dimred="PCA", colour_by="level1class")

plotReducedDim(sce.zeisel, dimred="PCA", ncomponents=4,
    colour_by="level1class")

set.seed(00101001101)

# runTSNE() stores the t-SNE coordinates in the reducedDims
# for re-use across multiple plotReducedDim() calls.
sce.zeisel <- runTSNE(sce.zeisel, dimred="PCA")
plotReducedDim(sce.zeisel, dimred="TSNE", colour_by="level1class")

set.seed(100)
sce.zeisel <- runTSNE(sce.zeisel, dimred="PCA", perplexity=5)
out5 <- plotReducedDim(sce.zeisel, dimred="TSNE",
    colour_by="level1class") + ggtitle("perplexity = 5")

set.seed(100)
sce.zeisel <- runTSNE(sce.zeisel, dimred="PCA", perplexity=20)
out20 <- plotReducedDim(sce.zeisel, dimred="TSNE",
    colour_by="level1class") + ggtitle("perplexity = 20")

set.seed(100)
sce.zeisel <- runTSNE(sce.zeisel, dimred="PCA", perplexity=80)
out80 <- plotReducedDim(sce.zeisel, dimred="TSNE", 
    colour_by="level1class") + ggtitle("perplexity = 80")
